You are using a JUnit 4 feature in which what you are doing is correct.
    
    @Test (expected = IllegalArgumentException.class)
    public void testDivException(){
        m.div(5, 0);
    }

But since after seeing your import, I can tell that you are using JUnit 5 for testing, I would like to tell you that the above method will not work. Since JUnit has its own **Assertions** class to handle the same. I will show you how.

    @Test
    public void testDivException() {
        
        Assertions.assertThrows(IllegalArgumentException.class, new Executable() {

			@Override
			public void execute() throws Throwable {

				m.div(5, 0);

			}
		});
    }

The above implementation will work with Java 7 and above. Now if you want to do the same thing using Lambda Expression in Java 8, do this:

    @Test
    public void testDivException(){
        Assertions.assertThrows(IllegalArgumentException.class, () -&gt; m.div(5, 0));
    }

You can read more about Assertion class and JUnit5 [here][1].


